snippet.textDisplay:
Did the people of the island have a say in this decision to go ahead with the fucked up useless airport?

Interesting topic I knew nothing about. But a terrible act of vandalistic journalism by “drinking the cool aid” and not trying to hold anyone to account for a terrible decision that may have cost this island it’s financial independence, and guaranteed financial dependence and servitude. Whom would that benefit? “Follow the money” is what you should always do as journalists, and @Wendover Productions is a total fucking failure here

Was there no other place on the island to put the airport? Was there no other way to orientate the runway? Assuming there were options, why was no study of the winds? If there was NO options for the runway, why was there no study of the winds?

The ONLY reason one can believe there was no study of the winds, was that someone KNEW that such a study would kill the project. THAT person should be in jail and THAT is what the documentary should be about, not this fucked up sugar coated feel good film about a fucked up bureaucratic decision that was made by whom?

Any st Helena residents reading this please tell me what it’s like living there, so interesting!
1. What’s it like living so isolated from anywhere else
2. What’s the community like, it seems like there’s loads of cultural diversity in religion and ethnicity, living in a pretty homogeneous part of Britain, I’m really interested in how these cultures coalesce. Do some cultures and traditions get borrowed from other cultures due to proximity?
Where I live, we don’t really have much of a community at all, we mostly try to keep away from each other as much as possible!

That being said, I can't imagine the night life is very much fun there. It looks like it would be beautiful to tour around, but that's like a day or two's worth the activities.

It seems like it wouldn't be an extraordinary trip, but it would be extremely expensive.

They should turn it into something like a hedonistic resort, with drugs and prostitutes, etc. They'd get a ton of travellers in from that, but I'm sure it would ruin the wholesome nature of the island.

snippet.textDisplay:
What a fascinating topic but dude why did you leave such a huge question hanging over the entire video? Was it a boondoggle from the start? Yes, the numbers are now on track; yes, lives have been saved; yes, the money needed to get spent but why didn't they account for the wind shear? What kind of airport engineers don't look at wind conditions on an island in the middle of the ocean? Was the criticism that the airport had a major design flaw making it impossible to provide high capacity service fair? Because, it sounds like yes, the designers screwed up in a major way and large aircraft which would have made flights economical will never be able to fly to the island and it's going to make using that "tool," as you put it, much more difficult to use.


A lovely story, some great footage and interesting but leaving out the answer to this question left me very unsatisfied -- and convinced that the criticism (though not the hyperbole) was totally justified.
snippet.textOriginal:
What a fascinating topic but *dude* why did you leave such a huge question hanging over the entire video? Was it a boondoggle from the start? Yes, the numbers are now on track; yes, lives have been saved; yes, the money needed to get spent but why didn't they account for the wind shear? What kind of airport engineers don't look at wind conditions on an island in the middle of the ocean? Was the criticism that the airport had a major design flaw making it impossible to provide high capacity service fair? Because, it sounds like *yes, the designers screwed up in a major way and large aircraft which would have made flights economical* will never be able to fly to the island and it's going to make using that "tool," as you put it, much more difficult to use. 


A lovely story, some great footage and interesting but leaving out the answer to this question left me very unsatisfied -- and convinced that the criticism (though _not_ the hyperbole) was totally justified.

Good documentary. I think it's narrow minded to only look at the airport as a profit source. It's in the United Kingdom's interest to subsidize this airport. And if you did get a huge tourism explosion, that comes with it's own list of pitfalls. I'd say the project was a success. It was a needed infrastructure improvement and it succeeds as that. Wouldn't the lives it's saved by being to care-flight people to better medical facilities be worth it?
All the sales pitches are due to the exact issue well shown in this video...what the media is going to say. Any major project a government tries to do has to be sold to the public. So you end up in a position where the media is looking for a criticism and in this case, it was easy to exploit negative ideas about it.

snippet.textDisplay: Ok, there is a wind shear issue, so they will write procedures for this specific airport and Pilots will receive more training during the IOE period for new pilots and ongoing training during recurrency. Not the only airport in the world with a wind shear issue. There is a learning curve, and over time with operational experience, the risks will be mitigated and regs will be written as to what you can or can't do specifically to St. Helena  Airport. It's going to take time to gain the experience since it's such a low use situation at the present. This is not too much different than  ERA's  Anchorage to Adak route. I had a friend that use to fly that one,  He flew a Metrolinner. It was if you go you, land. If there is doubt you didn't go.
